com.camerontec.util.concurrent.pool

Class MultiAcquirerConcurrentSharedObjectPool<E extends PoolableSharedObject>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.util.concurrent.pool.MultiAcquirerConcurrentSharedObjectPool<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - The shared object type.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    ConcurrentSharedObjectPool<E>

    public class MultiAcquirerConcurrentSharedObjectPool<E extends PoolableSharedObject>
extends Object
implements ConcurrentSharedObjectPool<E>
    Shared object pool implementation which has the following characteristics:
    • Fixed size
    • Only one thread may ever checkIn(PoolableSharedObject) check in} objects to the pool (typically this would be the pool owner).
    • Any thread may check out objects from the pool.

    When a thread attempts to check out an object from the pool:

    • If the pool has unused objects then an object from the pool checked out and returned, leaving an empty slot in the pool
    • If the pool has no unused objects (i.e is exhausted) then it returns null.

    When a thread attempts to check in an object to the pool:

    • If the pool has an empty slot then the object is checked back into the pool
    • If the pool has an no empty slots then the object is not checked back into the pool and therefore potentially becomes available for garbage collection. Note that in either case, the caller is never blocked awaiting an empty slot.

    This implementation works fine when shared objects are checked out and checked in on the same thread, however, it is likely to be less efficient than UnboundedReferencePool. Consider using that instead for the single threaded use case.

    See Also:
    SingleAcquirerConcurrentSharedObjectPool
